text=Introduction%0a===========%0a%0a(:GuildName: (Guild Name Here):)%0a%0aWelcome to {$:GuildName}. This guild recognizes that Astro Empires is a strategic war simulator. Economy is king because it fuels the war machines. As such, this guild takes a more militant approach to its activities. '''Our purpose is to attain the first rank for a guild in all categories.'''%0a%0aWe recognize that you may be a veteran player. If not, we still welcome%0ayou. Please read the [[TheTenSevenGuide|Ten-Seven Guide]] to build your%0aempire. This Policy Guide explains the guild's rank structure and%0aresponsibilities, diplomatic philosophy, and member goals. %0a%0a(:*toc:)%0a%0aHierarchy%0a==============%0a%0aThe {$:GuildName} guild has a different rank structure than most. Typically,%0aguilds base rank off of economy, fleet size, etc. Astro Empire (AE) bases%0arank off of a formula of economy, fleet and technology. Logically, a set%0aof ranks should derive from the AE levels as it is a superset of most%0aranks structures. This causes one to wonder why exotic ranks are%0acreated.%0a%0aBecause this is a military game, we adopt a hierarchy%0aof leadership. Players who are actively involved and able to lead others%0aare able to have a greater impact on the guild as a whole. %0a%0aRank Structure%0a--------------%0a%0aOur ranks derive from the player's responsibility (discussed below). A%0aplayer choses to become responsible for peers and becomes a Section%0aLeader.  A Section Leader is developed to be a Fleet Leader when each of%0ahis section members are themselves Section Leaders. Essentially, they%0adirect their section, and he directs them. A Fleet Leader is a Fleet%0aLeader whose section has become Section Leaders. The table below describes%0athis structure, and shows the insignia indicating a leader. Finally,%0athere are other indicators when a player is on probation or in jeopardy%0aof losing guild status.%0a%0a||class=structure cellspacing=0%0a||! Insignia ||! Title ||! Description ||%0a|| &#0198; || Commander || Overall responsible for guild management ||%0a|| &#8984; || Fleet Leader || Responsible for 4 Section (20 players) ||%0a|| &#0167; || Section Leader || Responsible for 4 Members ||%0a%0a'''Indicators:'''%0a* &#0222; Probation%0a* &#0215; In danger of being booted %0a%0aResponsibilities%0a----------------%0a%0aCommander%0a~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Commander is an honorary title bestowed regardless of rank. The%0aCommander manages the overall guild activities and chairs the Fleet%0aCounsel.%0a%0aFleet Leader%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aFleet Leaders manages activities with his team of Section Leaders. %0aThey are authorized to engage in minor wars. %0aThey are also guild recruiters.%0aThey are responsible for ensuring their Section Leaders are adequately%0ainvolved in their sections, and for helping their Section Leaders to become%0aFleet Leaders. %0aFleet Leaders are responsible for enforcing discipline (kicking idle or%0adisciplinary players). %0aFleet Leaders govern via the Fleet Counsel. %0aBecause of the size of a Fleet is 20 members, a Fleet Leader commands%0athe guild presence in his galaxy.%0aDuring mobilization, he will work with his Section Leaders to identify and%0aprioritize targets within his sphere of influence. During war, he will%0acoordinate activities and shift focus as necessary.%0aOnce a player is a fleet leader, he is expected to establish one base on%0aeach galaxy in the guild's area of interest (AOI).%0a%0aSection Leader%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aA Section Leader directs his section members. He is responsible for ensuring%0athat his members have adequate defenses, and helps coordinate support%0afor when one of his section members is attacked. %0aDuring war, section work together in attack and defense. %0aWhen each section member has fully developed defenses and an adequate%0aattack fleet, the members may then begin taking on junior members and%0abecome Section Leaders. %0aSection Leaders are responsible for identifying members of their section%0awho are idle or disciplinary problems. %0aDuring mobilization, the Section Leader designates targets and works%0awith his Fleet Leader to coordinate activities. %0aAt war, the Section Leader will direct section activities and ensure all%0amembers profit from the engagement. %0aA Section Leader must also maintain a current list of member bases and%0areport those base locations to the guild.%0aA Section Leader is considered ``Senior" when his subordinates have%0abegun mentoring a total of nine new members.%0a%0aSection Member%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aA Section Member is responsible for ensuring his bases are adequately%0adefended and that he builds an adequate attack fleet. %0aAdequacy is based on his tenure on Delta. %0aHe must continually work to improve his economy.%0aHe must report any combat he engages in (attack or defense). %0aAt peace, he will help monitor rival bases in his region. %0aDuring mobilization, he will report on target base locations and fleet sizes.  %0aAt war, he will attack rival bases as directed and support section%0amembers under attack.%0a%0aAdministrative Duties%0a---------------------%0a%0aThe following are important administrative that Fleet Leaders and%0aSenior Section Leaders may assume. Generally speaking, these members are%0aresponsible for obtaining and reporting information, or for smoothing%0acoordination for various activities. Some duties may be shared with more%0ajunior players as the guild requires.%0a%0aQuartermaster General (QMG)%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Quartermaster General is responsible for coordinating fleet actions%0aand tracking guild Jump Gates. He solicits new base locations,%0aconfirms guild ownership of known jump gates, and disseminates these%0alocations via the guild jump gate board '''''weekly'''''.%0a%0aDirector of Publicity%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Director of Publicity (DOP) is responsible for the guilds public%0aaffairs activities on the Astro Empires forums. This includes routine%0amonitoring of the board for postings referring to {$:Guildname}, and%0aproviding professional rebuttals as necessary. He will also announce%0amajor guild activities. This is a high-energy duty.%0a%0aDirector of Engineering%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Director of Engineering (DOE) is responsible for maintaining the guild%0apolicy for defenses and maintaining the master list of guild base%0alocations.%0a%0aDirector of Finance%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Director of Finance (DOF) manages trade routes between guild members and with other friendly guilds. His mandate is to maximize guild member's incomes.%0a%0aDirector of Training%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aThe Director of Training (DOT) ensures guild documentation on building a%0asuccessful empire is current and fully available to guild members. As%0aAstro Empires changes facets of game play (e.g. change values of unit%0aattributes), he will analyze the impact and share with the guild. (A%0alow-energy role.)%0a%0a:'''Director of Intelligence (DOI)''': Responsible for monitoring rival fleets and updating guild maps.%0a:'''Director of Security (DOS)''': Not sure yet. Perhaps managing members assigned to monitor rival and allied guilds.%0a%0aDiplomacy%0a=========%0a%0aThis guild's diplomacy must always serve its constituency and stated%0agoal. Members will support guild diplomacy.%0a%0aNon-Aggression Pacts%0a--------------------%0a%0aNon-Aggression Pacts (NAPs) is an agreement between two guilds to not%0aengage in all out war. These Pacts limit attacks against well-defended%0abases. Non-Aggression Pacts must be agreed to by consensus of the Fleet%0aLeaders who have the rival guild's bases within their area of%0aresponsiblity (AOR). For example, the other guild has presence in two%0agalaxies, both commanders must agree. If the guild expands into another%0agalaxy, then the NAP is open for reconsideration.%0aIn the event a NAP is terminated, no hostilities may initiate for five%0adays.%0aPlayers who violate a NAP with another guild are vulnerable to that%0aguild's full retaliation. This is likewise true of the rival guild's%0aviolator.%0a%0aAlliances%0a---------%0a%0aAlliances are either offensive or defensive in nature. They should also%0abe designated as either permanent or for a fixed duration. New alliances%0amust be agreed to by unanimous consent of the Fleet Counsel.%0a%0aCease Fires%0a-----------%0a%0aCease fires are temporary actions meant to cool tempers. They are either%0ainitiated to negotiate long-term peace, or to re-organize for resumption%0aof hostilities. The Fleet Counsel must agree to a cease fire by simple%0amajority.%0a%0aWar%0a-----%0a%0aWars are either minor or major. Minor wars may be waged within a Fleet%0aLeader's AOR with guilds that will not drag {$:GuildName} into a larger%0awar. Major wars are all other wars. Minor wars must be agreed to by a%0amajority in the Fleet Counsel. Major wars require unanimity.%0a%0a%0aScout Taps%0a----------%0a%0aThis guild permits Scout taps for Section Members only. This is generally%0abecause a Section Leader should normally have enough levels to not be able%0ato tap a rival player. However, the reason Leaders do not tap is in part%0ato allow junior players the opportunity to profit at another's lack of%0apreparation. Leaders are encouraged to announce Tappable locations so%0amembers of their section may profit.%0a%0aScrimages%0a---------%0a%0aA Scrimage is an agreed upon war between guilds. They are typically of a%0afixed duration. The purpose of a scrimage is to allow players to vent%0aoff steam, build experience, and prepare for larger wars. A Scrimage%0ashould be announced at least a week before it commences. It should be%0alimited in scope and last for not more than three days. Occupations and%0afleets should be withdrawn when the Scrimage is complete.%0a%0aOther%0a-----%0a%0adon't exploit the weak. Besides me, most members in my guild also tend to frown upon exploiting the weak. The only way to make profit is to have profitable battles, it does NOT have to be at the expense of weaker players. Taking down stronger or players in your level-range is FAR more fun.%0a%0a{$:GuildName} encourages scout taps. Just be prepared to defend%0ayourself. Scout taps against member bases subjects that member to being%0aput on report. We encourage defense build-up by allowing guild members%0ato tap one-another. As a new member is assigned a Section Leader who is%0aresponsible for him, taps should never occur.%0a%0aMember Goals%0a============%0a%0aAs a member of our guild, you are expected to help us fulfill the%0aguild's goals. This section discusses goals a member must make to remain%0ain the guild. Overall, the member is obligated to keep his Section Leader%0afully informed of his base locations and any situation that may impact%0athese goals.%0a%0aActivity%0a--------%0a%0aMembers are encouraged to visit Delta at least daily. Please also glance%0aover the forum and check the [CHANGES] page for any changes to policy.%0aInactivity for more than 3 days without prior notice to your next-level%0asuperior risks expulsion.%0a%0aDefensive Fleet Goals%0a---------------------%0a%0a||class=structure cellspacing=0%0a||! Quality ||! Size ||! Extras ||%0a||Superb||700x || 8x Disrupter Turrets, 20 Command Centers, P-Shield ||%0a||Great||600x || 6x Disrupter Turrets, 15 Command Centers, P-Shield ||%0a||Good||500x || 4x Disrupter Turrets, 10 Command Centers, P-Shield ||%0a||Fair||400x || 2x Disrupter Turrets, 10 Command Centers ||%0a||Mediocre||300x || 2x Best Turrets, 10 Command Centers ||%0a||Poor||200x || 2x Best Turrets, 5 Command Centers ||%0a||Terrible||100x || 1x Best Turrets ||%0a%0aThere are several levels of defensive fleet quality. The table above%0ahelps visualize the quality of fleets. Each month, a player should%0aattain the next level of fleet quality. Thus, a player should reach the%0aAdequate-quality fleet month by the end of his second month. It may be%0ahelpful for the member to use the emboldened letter in his fleet%0aidentifier to show its quality at a glance, although Fleets are%0aencouraged to adopt their own method as one method may reveal fleet%0aquality to rival guilds. Regardless, a scout taps against your bases are%0anot acceptable and you will be put on report.%0a%0aThe Standard%0a~~~~~~~~~~~~%0a%0aEach base must have at least a Good defensive fleet (500x Economy).%0aThus, a base generating 100 economy needs a 50,000 defense fleet. With%0athis fleet, the base must have 10 Command Centers, four Disrupter%0aTurrets, and a Planetary %0aShield.(:footnote Players know this is not possible until the research is completed.:)%0aA good ratio is 2000/100/50/1 (FT/CR/HC/BB), which generates a 57K%0afleet. (That ratio is a ``Basic Fleet".) A base with less than Mediocre%0afleet is considered undefended.%0a%0aInitial%0a~~~~~~~%0a%0aObviously the ideal is difficult to attain. Players do not need to start%0abuilding fleet until Day 6. By that day, players should immediately%0abuild 100 FT to cover their bases as well as one level of their best%0aturrets. The Initial goal must be met by Day 14. Players should then%0astart building a Minimal quality fleet.%0a%0aMedial%0a~~~~~~%0a%0aOnce the initial defenses are established, the member should seek to%0abuild a basic fleet.  A logical step between initial and medial defenses%0ais to build 1000 FT, then build the 100 CR, then 1000 FT (totalling 2000%0aFT), then 50 HC, then 1 BB. Once this fleet is built, the member should%0aexpand the fleet by that ratio until the ideal fleet size is attained%0afor that base.%0a%0aOffensive Fleet Goals%0a---------------------%0a%0aThe offensive fleet goal is easier to describe. The ideal fleet goal is%0aa 500 fleet multiple for each base. That is, each base supports two%0aideal defensive fleets---one is just offensive. Assuming you have ten%0abases at 100 econ, that is a 500,000 point offensive fleet. Your total%0afleet size is 1,000,000. By comparison, the highest fleet-ranked player%0aon Alpha has a 32.4 million point fleet. A good rule-of-thumb is to look%0aat your target rivals and have fifty percent more than you need to%0adefeat his fleets.%0a%0aScouting%0a--------%0a%0aEach member should keep track of rival bases within the Region of his%0abase. As one tenant of empire building is not to have more than one base%0ain a Region, this means that a player should be able to monitor at least nine%0aregions. There are 100 regions in a Galaxy. So, 11 players should be%0aable to keep tabs on an entire galaxy. That means that a Fleet should%0aeasily be able to monitor and dominate a Galaxy. Naturally, section members%0acan negotiate monitoring activities.%0a%0aWhen we mobilize, members will focus their attention on scouting guild%0abases with whom we will war against. This includes calculating what is%0anecessary to occupy rival bases and optimizing an offensive fleet.%0a%0aChanges%0a=======%0a%0aNovember 12%0a-----------%0a%0a* Dropped Fleet Leader as leader of 80 players.%0a* Section Leaders are now called Fleet Leaders%0a* Team Leaders are now Section Leaders.%0a%0a%0a(:comment This page has been edited using Pywe:)%0a(:title Guild Policy:)
